     1	# Rhei Plan Language Usage Guide
     2	
     3	This guide shows how to author Rhei Plan documents that conform to the
     4	[Rhei Language Specification](../rhei.spec.md). It focuses on practical
     5	patterns rather than formal grammar — consult the spec for precise rules.
     6	
     7	## A Minimal Plan
     8	
     9	The smallest valid plan declares a title, a `## Tasks` section, and at least
    10	one task with a `**State:**` field:
    11	
    12	```markdown
    13	# Rhei: First Plan
    14	
    15	## Tasks
    16	
    17	### Task 1: Set up the repository
    18	**State:** pending
    19	```
    20	
    21	Save this file with a `.rhei.md` extension, then validate it:
    22	
    23	```bash
    24	rhei validate my-plan.rhei.md
    25	```
    26	
    27	When no `**States:**` field is declared, the plan uses the built-in `rhei`
    28	state machine.
    29	
    30	## Authoring Workflow
    31	
    32	A typical plan grows in three passes:
    33	
    34	1. **Outline** — write the `# Rhei:` title and draft `## Overview`,
    35	   `## Context`, or similar prose sections that motivate the work.
    36	2. **Break down** — add a `## Tasks` section and enumerate tasks with
    37	   numeric or named ids. Give every task a `**State:**` (usually `draft`
    38	   or `pending`) and a short description.
    39	3. **Refine** — add `**Prior:**` dependencies, split tasks into child
    40	   task nodes, and transition states as work progresses.
    41	
    42	Keep content sections before `## Tasks`. Everything after `## Tasks` is
    43	parsed as task structure.
    44	
    45	## Tasks and Child Tasks
    46	
    47	### Numeric vs named tasks
    48	
    49	Numeric task ids (`### Task 1:`) are ordered and may contain child tasks.
    50	Named task ids (`### Task setup:`) are useful for conceptual anchors that
    51	other tasks depend on — they must not declare child tasks.
    52	
    53	```markdown
    54	### Task infra: Provision cloud resources
    55	**State:** pending
    56	
    57	### Task 1: Deploy application
    58	**State:** pending
    59	**Prior:** Task infra
    60	```
    61	
    62	### Child task nodes
    63	
    64	Root tasks live at `###` (H3). Child tasks are declared at the next heading
    65	level (`####`, H4), their children at `#####` (H5), and so on. A child task
    66	is a full task node — it carries its own `**State:**` line and may declare
    67	`**Prior:**` dependencies just like a root task.
    68	
    69	Child ids extend the parent id by exactly one segment, joined with a dot.
    70	So children of `Task 2` are `Task 2.1`, `Task 2.2`, …; a child of
    71	`Task api.cache` is `Task api.cache.fix`. Numeric segments are ordered;
    72	named segments are arbitrary labels. Duplicate sibling ids under one parent
    73	are rejected.
    74	
    75	```markdown
    76	### Task 2: Implement login flow
    77	**State:** pending
    78	
    79	#### Task 2.1: Wire OAuth callback
    80	**State:** pending
    81	
    82	#### Task 2.2: Persist session tokens
    83	**State:** pending
    84	**Prior:** Task 2.1
    85	```
    86	
    87	### Depth and node kinds
    88	
    89	By default a plan permits a root task plus one level of children, using
    90	only the `Task` node kind. Plans that need deeper trees or additional
    91	kinds (for example `Bug`) may declare a `structure` block in the plan
    92	frontmatter:
    93	
    94	```yaml
    95	structure:
    96	  maxLevels: 4
    97	  nodeKinds: [task, bug]
    98	```
    99	
   100	`maxLevels` counts from the root (a root task alone has `maxLevels: 1`;
   101	root plus direct children is `maxLevels: 2`). Validation rejects nodes
   102	that exceed the declared depth or use a heading kind not listed in
   103	`nodeKinds`. When `structure` is omitted, the defaults are
   104	`maxLevels: 2, nodeKinds: [task]`.
   105	
   106	## Metadata
   107	
   108	`**State:**` is mandatory and must be the first line after the task header.
   109	`**Prior:**` is optional and, when present, must immediately follow
   110	`**State:**`.
   111	
   112	```markdown
   113	### Task 3: Ship release notes
   114	**State:** agent-review
   115	**Prior:** Task 1, Task 2
   116	```
   117	
   118	### State values with spaces
   119	
   120	Single-word states are written bare. Multi-word states must be wrapped in
   121	backticks:
   122	
   123	```markdown
   124	**State:** `in review`
   125	```
   126	
   127	The state value must be defined in the active states file — multi-word
   128	states typically require a custom states file such as
   129	[`examples/states-with-spaces.yaml`](../../examples/states-with-spaces.yaml).
   130	
   131	### Dependencies
   132	
   133	List prerequisites by id, separated by commas. References must resolve to
   134	tasks defined in the same document, and the dependency graph must stay
   135	acyclic. A task must not list itself or any ancestor as a prerequisite: a
   136	child task cannot use its parent as `**Prior:**`. If follow-up work must wait
   137	for a completed parent task, write that follow-up as a top-level sibling and
   138	point `**Prior:**` at the completed task.
   139	
   140	```markdown
   141	**Prior:** Task 1, Task design, Task 4
   142	```
   143	
   144	```markdown
   145	#### Task fetch-prs.ci-failure-5227: Triage CI failure
   146	**State:** pending
   147	**Prior:** Task fetch-prs    ← Invalid when `fetch-prs` is this task's parent
   148	```
   149	
   150	`**Prior:**` is the markdown authoring form. SDKs expose the same data under
   151	idiomatic names — `task.metadata.dependsOn` (TypeScript/JavaScript, Java,
   152	CLI JSON) or `task.metadata.depends_on` (Python). See
   153	[Transitions Specification — Naming conventions](rhei-transitions.spec.md#naming-conventions)
   154	for the full table.
   155	
   156	## Using a Custom State Machine
   157	
   158	To reuse one state machine across plans, declare it on the line directly
   159	after the `# Rhei:` title:
   160	
   161	```markdown
   162	# Rhei: Content Refresh
   163	**States:** content-workflow
   164	```
   165	
   166	The `name` field in the resolved YAML file must match this value. By
   167	default, Rhei resolves that file automatically from `states.yaml` next to
   168	the plan (single-file plans) or at the workspace root (directory
   169	workspaces). Pass `--state-machine <path>` only when you want to override
   170	that automatic lookup:
   171	
   172	```bash
   173	rhei validate plans/content-refresh.rhei.md
   174	```
   175	
   176	See the [States Specification](rhei-states.spec.md) for the states file format.
   177	
   178	## Common Pitfalls
   179	
   180	- **Missing `**State:**`** — every task header must be followed by a
   181	  `**State:**` line.
   182	- **Metadata out of order** — `**Prior:**` must come after `**State:**`,
   183	  not before.
   184	- **Child task under a named task** — only numeric task ids may own
   185	  child tasks.
   186	- **Cross-plan references** — `**Prior:**` only resolves within one
   187	  document; to model cross-plan dependencies, keep those tasks in the
   188	  same file.
   189	- **Unknown state** — validation fails if a `**State:**` value is not
   190	  declared in the active states file.
   191	- **Duplicate ids** — two tasks with the same id (numeric or named) are
   192	  rejected, as are duplicate child task ids under one parent.
   193	
   194	## Worked Examples
   195	
   196	The [`examples/`](../../examples/) directory contains end-to-end plans that
   197	exercise the patterns above:
   198	
   199	- [`release-automation.rhei.md`](../../examples/release-automation.rhei.md) —
   200	  mixed numeric and named task ids with fenced code inside a child task.
   201	- [`human-review-loop.rhei.md`](../../examples/human-review-loop.rhei.md) —
   202	  multi-state workflow with chained dependencies.
   203	- [`escaped-state-values.rhei.md`](../../examples/escaped-state-values.rhei.md) —
   204	  multi-word state values paired with a custom states file.
   205	
   206	## Advancing Task States with `rhei transition`
   207	
   208	While `**State:**` values can be edited by hand, the `rhei transition`
   209	command provides an atomic, validated way to advance a task's state:
   210	
   211	```bash
   212	rhei transition my-plan.rhei.md --task 1 --from pending --to in-progress
   213	```
   214	
   215	The command:
   216	
   217	1. **Acquires a file lock** on the plan to prevent concurrent writes.
   218	2. **Reads the current state** of the specified task.
   219	3. **Compare-and-swap** — if the task's current state does not match
   220	   `--from`, the command fails with a conflict error. This prevents two
   221	   agents from claiming the same task.
   222	4. **Validates the transition** against the state machine — illegal
   223	   transitions are rejected before any write occurs.
   224	5. **Writes the new state** to the markdown and releases the lock.
   225	
   226	### Flags
   227	
   228	| Flag             | Required | Description                                     |
   229	| ---------------- | -------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
   230	| `--task <id>`    | Yes      | Task id (numeric or named) to transition        |
   231	| `--from <state>` | Yes      | Expected current state (compare-and-swap guard) |
   232	| `--to <state>`   | Yes      | Target state                                    |
   233	| `--json`         | No       | Emit result as JSON instead of plain text       |
   234	
   235	On success the command prints the updated state. On conflict (another
   236	agent already transitioned the task) it exits non-zero with a message
   237	indicating the actual current state. Agents should re-read the plan and
   238	re-select when this happens.
   239	
   240	### Parallel safety
   241	
   242	When multiple agents work on the same plan, `rhei transition` is the
   243	coordination primitive. Because the `--from` flag acts as a
   244	compare-and-swap guard, only one agent can win a race on the same task —
   245	the loser gets a clean error and picks a different task. See
   246	[How Rhei Is Used — Pattern 3](rhei-usage.spec.md) for the full
   247	parallel-workers pattern.
   248	
   249	## Next Steps
   250	
   251	- Read the [Plan Language Specification](../rhei.spec.md) for the
   252	  formal grammar and semantic constraints.
   253	- Browse the [States Specification](rhei-states.spec.md) to define project-
   254	  specific workflows.
   255	- Use `rhei render --format github` to produce review-friendly views of
   256	  a plan, or `--format progress` for a terminal overview.
   257	
   258	### Progress format
   259	
   260	`--format progress` renders the plan as a compact ANSI terminal report intended
   261	for quick navigation.  Its structure is:
   262	
   263	```text
   264	Rhei: <title>
   265	<SectionTitle>:
   266	  <line 1 of section content>
   267	  <line 2 of section content>
   268	  …
   269	* Task <id>: <title>  [STATE]
   270	  - Prior: Task <id>, …          (omitted when empty)
   271	  - <id>.<sub>: <child task title>
   272	  …
   273	```
   274	
   275	Content sections (e.g. `## Overview`, `## Success Metrics`) are rendered in
   276	full, with each non-blank line indented by two spaces under the section title.
   277	No content is truncated.  This ensures the progress view is a useful navigation
   278	surface even for plans with substantial product context.

