   364	
   365	## Semantic Constraints
   366	
   367	Beyond the syntactic rules, the following semantic constraints must be validated:
   368	
   369	The grammar tolerates optional blank lines immediately after `## Tasks` in a
   370	single-file plan and at the start of a workspace task file. Implementations
   371	should accept those blank lines in both formats.
   372	
   373	Throughout this specification, a *task node* means any authored node entry at
   374	heading level `###`, `####`, `#####`, or `######` whose keyword is declared in
   375	`structure.nodeKinds` (or the default `[task]` when omitted). Root task nodes
   376	live directly under `## Tasks`; deeper task nodes are children of the nearest
   377	shallower task node above them.
   378	
   379	Throughout this specification, a *terminal state* means any state marked
   380	`final: true` in the active state machine. In the built-in `rhei` machine, the
   381	terminal states are `completed` and `cancelled`.
   382	
   383	Dependency readiness is defined by that terminal-state rule alone: a task is
   384	ready with respect to `**Prior:**` only when every referenced dependency is in
   385	a terminal state. State-machine `instructions` text is descriptive guidance for
   386	agents and must not narrow or override this readiness rule unless the machine
   387	introduces a separate normative field for that purpose.
   388	
   389	When frontmatter defines a `structure` map, the following keys are meaningful
   390	to this specification:
   391	
   392	- `structure.maxLevels` — maximum allowed task depth, counted from level 1 at
   393	  `### <kind> ...`. Valid values are `1` through `4`. If omitted, the default
   394	  is `2`.
   395	- `structure.nodeKinds` — allowed node-kind keywords for task nodes. Values
   396	  must be unique `IDENTIFIER`s. Parsing and validation normalize them
   397	  case-insensitively. If omitted, the default is `[task]`.
   398	
   399	`rhei` is a reserved node-kind name. It denotes the plan itself and is
   400	always the kind of the single root node at level 0. `rhei` must not appear
   401	in `structure.nodeKinds`, and it must not appear as a key under
   402	`node_policy.by_type` in the active state machine. A non-root node must
   403	never use the `rhei` kind.
   404	
   405	The heading keyword is the node kind. By convention, authored headings render
   406	that keyword in Title Case (`task` -> `Task`, `bug` -> `Bug`), but semantic
   407	matching is case-insensitive.
   408	
   409	Each node's state policy — which state it starts in and which states it may
   410	ever hold — is resolved from the active state machine's `profiles` and
   411	`node_policy` blocks. The root (always `rhei`) resolves through
   412	`node_policy.root`; all other nodes resolve through `node_policy.overrides`,
   413	then `node_policy.by_type[<kind>]`, then `node_policy.default`. See the
   414	[States Specification](specs/rhei-states.spec.md#node-policy) for the full
   415	resolution order and validation rules.
   416	
   417	### 1. Dependency Integrity
   418	
   419	All task references in `**Prior:**` fields must resolve to existing task nodes
   420	in the same logical plan: in a Single-File Plan that means the same document,
   421	and in a Directory Workspace that means the merged workspace graph across all
   422	task files under `tasks/`. A `**Prior:**` list must not contain duplicate
   423	references, must not reference its own task (self-reference is a 1-cycle), and
   424	must not reference any ancestor of the task. A child task cannot list its
   425	parent as `**Prior:**`; if generated follow-up work must wait for a completed
   426	parent task, author that follow-up as a top-level sibling with `**Prior:**`
   427	pointing at the completed task.
   428	
   429	```markdown
   430	### Task 2: Implementation
   431	**State:** pending
   432	**Prior:** Task 1, Task 3    ← Task 1 and Task 3 must exist
   433	```
   434	
   435	Directory Workspace example:
   436	
   437	```markdown
   438	# tasks/backend.md
   439	### Task api: Build API
   440	**State:** pending
   441	
   442	# tasks/frontend.md
   443	### Task ui: Build UI
   444	**State:** pending
   445	**Prior:** Task api    ← Valid: resolves across the merged workspace graph
   446	```
   447	
   448	When a dependency reference includes a node kind, that kind must match the
   449	declared kind of the referenced node.
   450	
   451	Invalid child dependency example:
   452	
   453	```markdown
   454	### Task fetch-prs: Fetch pull requests
   455	**State:** completed
   456	
   457	#### Task fetch-prs.ci-failure-5227: Triage CI failure
   458	**State:** pending
   459	**Prior:** Task fetch-prs    ← ERROR: child cannot depend on its parent
   460	```
   461	
   462	### 2. State Validity
   463	
   464	All state values must be defined in the associated states configuration. By default, that configuration is loaded from the plan's auto-discovered `states.yaml` when `**States:**` is declared, or from the built-in `rhei` state machine when it is omitted. `--state-machine <path>` may override the auto-discovered file.
   465	
   466	In addition, each authored `**State:**` must be a member of the node's
   467	resolved profile's `allowed` set, as determined by the active state
   468	machine's `node_policy`. A state that is defined in the global `states`
   469	block but excluded from the node's resolved profile is a validation error
   470	on that node.
   471	
   472	State-name rendering is normative across the plan and state-machine specs:
   473	
   474	- A canonical state name that matches `IDENTIFIER` exactly may be written bare:
   475	  `**State:** pending`.
   476	- Any canonical state name containing whitespace or any character outside
   477	  `IDENTIFIER` must be written in backticks, using the backticked forms shown
   478	  in the examples below.
   479	- Inside the backticked form, `\\` encodes a literal backslash and `\`` encodes
   480	  a literal backtick.
   481	- When related specs describe artifact or transition state names as arbitrary
   482	  YAML strings, this markdown encoding is the corresponding representation in a
   483	  plan file.
   484	
   485	When a state machine state declares `visits: <n>`, the authored markdown may
   486	encode later counted visits directly in `**State:**` using a `-<visit>` suffix:
   487	
   488	```markdown
   489	**State:** review      ← first visit (implicit)
   490	**State:** review-2    ← second visit
   491	**State:** `human review-3`  ← third visit for a spaced state name
   492	```
   493	
   494	The canonical state machine state is the unsuffixed base name (`review`,
   495	`human review`). The suffix is only valid for states that declare `visits`, must
   496	be greater than `1`, and must not exceed the declared visit budget.
   497	
   498	Parsing rule for ambiguous names:
   499	
   500	1. Remove optional surrounding backticks and first try to match the rendered
   501	   value exactly against a loaded state name.
   502	2. Only if no exact match exists may an implementation interpret a trailing
   503	   `-<digits>` suffix as a counted visit.
   504	3. In that case, the unsuffixed base name must itself exactly match a loaded
   505	   state name, and the parsed visit count becomes the suffix value.
   506	
   507	This means a machine that defines a literal state named `review-2` treats
   508	`**State:** review-2` as that canonical state on visit 1. It is only parsed as
   509	"state `review`, visit 2" when no literal `review-2` state exists.
   510	
   511	Additional examples:
   512	
   513	```markdown
   514	**State:** pending                 ← canonical state `pending`
   515	**State:** `human review`          ← canonical state `human review`
   516	**State:** `qa/review`             ← canonical state `qa/review`
   517	**State:** `security.review-2`     ← canonical state `security.review`, visit 2
   518	**State:** `review-2`              ← either literal state `review-2` or, if absent, state `review` visit 2
   519	```
   520	
   521	### 3. Acyclic Dependencies
   522	
   523	The task dependency graph must be a Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG). Circular dependencies are forbidden:
   524	
   525	```markdown
   526	### Task 1: First
   527	**State:** pending
   528	**Prior:** Task 2    ← ERROR: creates cycle
   529	
   530	### Task 2: Second
   531	**State:** pending
   532	**Prior:** Task 1    ← ERROR: creates cycle
   533	```
   534	
   535	### 4. Hierarchical Task Consistency
   536	
   537	Task nodes form a tree. Authored heading depth and task-id path depth must
   538	match:
   539	
   540	- a `### <kind> ...` node must use a one-segment id such as `1` or `api`
   541	- a `#### <kind> ...` node must use a two-segment id such as `1.1` or `api.cache`
   542	- a `##### <kind> ...` node must use a three-segment id
   543	- a `###### <kind> ...` node must use a four-segment id
   544	
   545	Child task ids must extend their parent id by exactly one segment, and sibling
   546	task ids must be unique within the same parent.
   547	
   548	```markdown
   549	### Task 2: Parent Task
   550	**State:** pending
   551	
   552	#### Task 2.1: Valid child
   553	**State:** pending
   554	
   555	#### Task 3.1: Invalid child
   556	**State:** pending
   557	                         ← ERROR: child id does not extend parent id `2`
   558	
   559	#### Task 2.1: Duplicate sibling
   560	**State:** pending

